# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: langchain
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:langchain/langchain] LangChain was launched in October 2022 as an open source project by Harrison Chase, while working at machine learning startup Robust Intelligence.
[src:langchain/langchain] In April 2023, LangChain had incorporated and the new startup raised over $20 million in funding at a valuation of at least $200 million from venture firm Sequoia Capital, a week after announcing a $10 million seed investment from Benchmark.
[src:langchain/langchain] In the third quarter of 2023, the LangChain Expression Language (LCEL) was introduced, which provides a declarative way to define chains of actions.
[src:langchain/langchain] In October 2023 LangChain introduced LangServe, a deployment tool to host LCEL code as a production-ready API.
[src:langchain/langchain] In February 2024 LangChain released LangSmith, a closed-source observability and evaluation platform for LLM applications, and announced a US $25 million Series A led by Sequoia Capital.
[src:langchain/langchain] On 14 May 2025 the company launched LangGraph Platform into general availability, providing managed infrastructure for deploying long-running, stateful AI agents.
[src:langchain/langchain] In April 2025, LangChain was featured in the Forbes AI 50 list.
[src:langchain/langchain] LangChain's developers highlight the framework's applicability to use-cases including chatbots, retrieval-augmented generation, document summarization, and synthetic data generation.
[src:langchain/langchain] *InfoWorld* described LangChain as a software development kit that simplifies the connection between large language models and external applications through a unified API.
[src:langchain/langchain] The magazine also wrote that it can be used to bring in context from sources such as PDFs, web pages, CSV files and relational databases, while making it easier for developers to change the underlying model without major code changes.
[src:langchain/langchain] As of April 2023, it can read from more than 50 document types and data sources.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] A **large language model** (**LLM**) is a neural network trained on a vast amount of text for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can typically generate, summarize, translate, and analyze text in many contexts, and are a foundational technology behind modern chatbots.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Biased or inaccurate training data can make an LLM's output less reliable.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are typically based on transformer architecture.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) are a type of LLM that is pre-trained to predict the next word.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] GPTs are then often fine-tuned to follow instructions and to behave as assistants.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Benchmark evaluations for LLMs attempt to measure model reasoning, factual accuracy, alignment, and safety.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Before the emergence of transformer-based models in 2017, some language models were considered large relative to the computational and data constraints of their time.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In the early 1990s, IBM's statistical models pioneered word alignment techniques for machine translation, laying the groundwork for corpus-based language modeling.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In 2001, a smoothed *n*-gram model, such as those employing Kneser–Ney smoothing, trained on 300 million words, achieved state-of-the-art perplexity on benchmark tests.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] During the 2000s, with the rise of widespread internet access, researchers began compiling massive text datasets from the web ("web as corpus") to train statistical language models.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Moving beyond *n*-gram models, researchers started in 2000 to use neural networks as language models.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Following the breakthrough of deep neural networks in image classification around 2012, similar architectures were adapted for language tasks.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] This shift was marked by the development of word embeddings (e.g., Word2Vec by Mikolov in 2013) and sequence-to-sequence (seq2seq) models using LSTM.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In 2016, Google transitioned its translation service to neural machine translation (NMT), replacing statistical phrase-based models with deep recurrent neural networks.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] These early NMT systems used LSTM-based encoder-decoder architectures, as they preceded the invention of transformers.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] At the 2017 NeurIPS conference, Google researchers introduced the transformer architecture in their landmark paper "Attention Is All You Need".
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] This paper's goal was to improve upon 2014 seq2seq technology, and was based mainly on the attention mechanism developed by Bahdanau et al. in 2014.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The following year in 2018, BERT was introduced and quickly became "ubiquitous".
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Though the original transformer has both encoder and decoder blocks, BERT is an encoder-only model.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Academic and research usage of BERT began to decline in 2023, following rapid improvements in the abilities of decoder-only models (such as GPT) to solve tasks via prompting.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Although decoder-only GPT-1 was introduced in 2018, it was GPT-2 in 2019 that caught widespread attention because OpenAI claimed to have initially deemed it too powerful to release publicly, out of fear of malicious use.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] GPT-3 in 2020 went a step further and as of 2025 is available only via API with no offering of downloading the model to execute locally.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] But it was the consumer-facing chatbot ChatGPT in late 2022 that received extensive media coverage and public attention by 2023.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The 2023 GPT-4 was praised for its increased accuracy and as a "holy grail" for its multimodal capabilities.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI did not reveal the high-level architecture and the number of parameters of GPT-4.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The release of ChatGPT led to an uptick in LLM usage across several research subfields of computer science, including robotics, software engineering, and societal impact work.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In 2024, OpenAI released the reasoning model OpenAI o1, which generates long chains of thought before returning a final answer.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Many LLMs with parameter counts comparable to those of OpenAI's GPT series have been developed.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Since 2022, weights-available models have been gaining popularity, especially at first with BLOOM and LLaMA, though both have restrictions on usage and deployment.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Mistral AI's open-weight models Mistral 7B and Mixtral 8x7B have a more permissive Apache License.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, DeepSeek released DeepSeek R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight model that performs comparably to OpenAI o1 but at a much lower price per token for users.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Since 2023, many LLMs have been trained to be multimodal, having the ability to also process or generate other types of data, such as images, audio, or 3D meshes.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Open-weight LLMs have become more influential since 2023.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] (2025), community-driven contributions to open-weight models improve their efficiency and performance via collaborative platforms such as Hugging Face.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] As machine learning algorithms process numbers rather than text, the text must be converted to numbers.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, a vocabulary is decided upon, then integer indices are arbitrarily but uniquely assigned to each vocabulary entry, and finally, an embedding is associated with the integer index.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Algorithms include byte-pair encoding (BPE) and WordPiece.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] There are also special tokens serving as control characters, such as `[MASK]` for masked-out token (as used in BERT), and `[UNK]` ("unknown") for characters not appearing in the vocabulary.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Also, some special symbols are used to denote special text formatting.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] For example, "Ġ" denotes a preceding whitespace in RoBERTa and GPT and "##" denotes continuation of a preceding word in BERT.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Tokenization also compresses the datasets.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Because LLMs generally require input to be an array that is not jagged, the shorter texts must be "padded" until they match the length of the longest one.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] As an example, consider a tokenizer based on byte-pair encoding.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, all unique characters (including blanks and punctuation marks) are treated as an initial set of *n*-grams (i.e. initial set of uni-grams).
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Successively the most frequent pair of adjacent characters is merged into a bi-gram and all instances of the pair are replaced by it.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] All occurrences of adjacent pairs of (previously merged) *n*-grams that most frequently occur together are then again merged into even lengthier *n*-gram, until a vocabulary of prescribed size is obtained.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] After a tokenizer is trained, any text can be tokenized by it, as long as it does not contain characters not appearing in the initial-set of uni-grams.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In the context of training LLMs, datasets are typically cleaned by removing low-quality, duplicated, or toxic data.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Cleaned datasets can increase training efficiency and lead to improved downstream performance.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] A trained LLM can be used to clean datasets for training a further LLM.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] With the increasing proportion of LLM-generated content on the web, data cleaning in the future may include filtering out such content.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] LLM-generated content can pose a problem if the content is similar to human text (making filtering difficult) but of lower quality (degrading performance of models trained on it).
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Training of largest language models might need more linguistic data than naturally available, or that the naturally occurring data is of insufficient quality.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In these cases, synthetic data might be used.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is a type of foundation model (large X model) trained on language.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In particular, GPT models are first pretrained to predict the next word on a large amount of data, before being fine-tuned.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Substantial infrastructure is necessary for training the largest models.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The tendency towards larger models is visible in the list of large language models.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] For example, the training of GPT-2 (i.e. a 1.5-billion-parameter model) in 2019 cost $50,000, while training of the PaLM (i.e. a 540-billion-parameter model) in 2022 cost $8 million, and Megatron-Turing NLG 530B (in 2021) cost around $11 million.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The qualifier "large" in "large language model" is inherently vague, as there is no definitive threshold for the number of parameters required to qualify as "large".
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Before being fine-tuned, most LLMs are next-token predictors.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The fine-tuning shapes the LLM's behavior via techniques like reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) or constitutional AI.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Instruction fine-tuning is a form of supervised learning used to teach LLMs to follow user instructions.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In 2022, OpenAI demonstrated InstructGPT, a version of GPT-3 similarly fine-tuned to follow instructions.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] RLHF involves training a reward model to predict which text humans prefer.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Then, the LLM can be fine-tuned through reinforcement learning to better satisfy this reward model.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Since humans typically prefer truthful, helpful and harmless answers, RLHF favors such answers.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are generally based on the transformer architecture, which leverages an attention mechanism that enables the model to process relationships between all elements in a sequence simultaneously, regardless of their distance from each other.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] (2023) proposed state-space representation models as an alternative.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] 117M parameter sized) GPT-2 model has had twelve attention heads and a context window of only 1k tokens.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] A mixture of experts (MoE) is a machine learning architecture in which multiple specialized neural networks ("experts") work together, with a gating mechanism that routes each input to the most appropriate expert(s).
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Mixtures of experts can reduce inference costs, as only a fraction of the parameters are used for each input.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Typically, LLMs are trained with single or half-precision floating point numbers (float32 and float16).
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] One float16 has 16 bits, or 2 bytes, and so one billion parameters require 2 gigabytes.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The largest models typically have more than 100 billion parameters, which places them outside the range of most consumer electronics.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] It is possible to fine-tune quantized models using low-rank adaptation.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Beyond basic text generation, various techniques have been developed to extend LLM capabilities, including the use of external tools and data sources, improved reasoning on complex problems, and enhanced instruction-following or autonomy through prompting methods.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In 2020, OpenAI researchers demonstrated that their new model GPT-3 could understand what format to use given a few rounds of Q and A (or other type of task) in the input data as example, thanks in part due to the RLHF technique.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] This technique, called *few-shot prompting*, allows LLMs to be adapted to any task without requiring fine-tuning.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Also in 2022, it was found that the base GPT-3 model can generate an instruction based on user input.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The generated instruction along with user input is then used as input to another instance of the model under a "Instruction: [...], Input: [...], Output:" format.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The other instance is able to complete the output and often produces the correct answer in doing so.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The ability to "self-instruct" makes LLMs able to bootstrap themselves toward a correct answer.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can be turned into a chatbot by specializing it for conversation.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] User input is prefixed with a marker such as "Q:" or "User:" and the LLM is asked to predict the output after a fixed "A:" or "Assistant:".
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] This type of model became commercially available in 2022 with ChatGPT, a sibling model of InstructGPT fine-tuned to accept and produce dialog-formatted text based on GPT-3.5.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] It could similarly follow user instructions.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Before the stream of User and Assistant lines, a chat context usually starts with a few lines of overarching instructions, from a role called "developer" or "system" to convey a higher authority than the user's input.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) is an approach that integrates LLMs with document retrieval systems.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Given a query, a document retriever is called to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] This is usually done by encoding the query and the documents into vectors, then finding the documents with vectors (usually stored in a vector database) most similar to the vector of the query.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The LLM then generates an output based on both the query and context included from the retrieved documents.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Tool use is a mechanism that enables LLMs to interact with external systems, applications, or data sources.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] It can allow LLMs to, for example, fetch real-time information from an API or to execute code.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] A program separate from the LLM watches the output stream of the LLM for a special tool-calling syntax.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] When these special tokens appear, the program calls the tool accordingly and feeds its output back into the LLM's input stream.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Early tool-using LLMs were fine-tuned on the use of specific tools.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] But fine-tuning LLMs for the ability to read API documentation and call APIs correctly has greatly expanded the range of tools accessible to an LLM.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is typically not an autonomous agent by itself, as it lacks the ability to interact with dynamic environments, recall past behaviors, and plan future actions.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] But it can be transformed into an agent by adding supporting elements: the role (profile) and the surrounding environment of an agent can be additional inputs to the LLM, while memory can be integrated as a tool or provided as additional input.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Instructions and input patterns are used to make the LLM plan actions and tool use is used to potentially carry out these actions.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In the DEPS ("describe, explain, plan and select") method, an LLM is first connected to the visual world via image descriptions.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] It is then prompted to produce plans for complex tasks and behaviors based on its pretrained knowledge and the environmental feedback it receives.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The *Reflexion method* constructs an agent that learns over multiple episodes.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] At the end of each episode, the LLM is given the record of the episode, and prompted to think up "lessons learned", which would help it perform better at a subsequent episode.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] These "lessons learned" are stored as a form of long-term memory and given to the agent in the subsequent episodes.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Monte Carlo tree search can use an LLM as rollout heuristic.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] When a programmatic world model is not available, an LLM can also be prompted with a description of the environment to act as world model.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Multiple agents with memory can interact socially.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] A 2022 paper demonstrated a separate technique called *chain-of-thought prompting*, which makes the LLM break the question down autonomously.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is given some examples where the "assistant" verbally breaks down the thought process before arriving at an answer.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The LLM mimics these examples and also tries to spend some time generating intermediate steps before providing the final answer.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] This additional step elicited by prompting improves the correctness of the LLM on relatively complex questions.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] On math word questions, a prompted model can exceed even fine-tuned GPT-3 with a verifier.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Chain-of-thought can also be elicited by simply adding an instruction like "Let's think step by step" to the prompt, in order to encourage the LLM to proceed methodically instead of trying to directly guess the answer.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In late 2024, a new approach to LLM development emerged with "reasoning models".
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] These are trained to generate step-by-step analysis before producing final answers, enabling better results on complex tasks, for instance in mathematics, coding and logic.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI introduced this concept with their o1 model in September 2024, followed by o3 in April 2025.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] On the International Mathematics Olympiad qualifying exam problems, GPT-4o achieved 13% accuracy while o1 reached 83%.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, the Chinese company DeepSeek released DeepSeek-R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight reasoning model that achieved comparable performance to OpenAI's o1 while being significantly more cost-effective to operate.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Unlike proprietary models from OpenAI, DeepSeek-R1's open-weight nature allowed researchers to study and build upon the algorithm, though its training data remained private.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] These reasoning models typically require more computational resources per query compared to traditional LLMs, as they perform more extensive processing to work through problems step by step.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Multimodality means having multiple modalities, where a "modality" refers to a type of input or output, such as video, image, audio, text, proprioception, etc.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] For example, Google PaLM model was fine-tuned into a multimodal model and applied to robotic control.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] LLaMA models have also been turned multimodal using the tokenization method, to allow image inputs, and video inputs.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] GPT-4o can process and generate text, audio and images.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] A common method to create multimodal models out of an LLM is to "tokenize" the output of a trained encoder.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Concretely, one can construct an LLM that can understand images as follows: take a trained LLM, and take a trained image encoder E .
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Make a small multilayer perceptron f , so that for any image y , the post-processed vector $f(E(y))$ has the same dimensions as an encoded token.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Then, one can interleave text tokens and image tokens.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The compound model is then fine-tuned on an image-text dataset.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] This basic construction can be applied with more sophistication to improve the model.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The image encoder may be frozen to improve stability.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] This type of method, where embeddings from multiple modalities are fused and the predictor is trained on the combined embeddings, is called *early fusion*.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Another method, called *intermediate fusion*, involves each modality being first processed independently to obtain modality-specific representations; then these intermediate representations are fused together.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In general, cross-attention is used for integrating information from different modalities.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] As an example, the Flamingo model uses cross-attention layers to inject visual information into its pre-trained language model.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can handle programming languages similarly to how they handle natural languages.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] No special change in token handling is needed as code, like human language, is represented as plain text.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can generate code based on problems or instructions written in natural language.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] They can also describe code in natural language or translate it into other programming languages.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] They were originally used as a code completion tool, but advances have moved them towards automatic programming.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Services such as GitHub Copilot offer LLMs specifically trained, fine-tuned, or prompted for programming.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In computational biology, transformer-based architectures, such as DNA LLMs, have also proven useful in analyzing biological sequences: protein, DNA, and RNA.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] With proteins they appear able to capture a degree of "grammar" from the amino-acid sequence, by mapping that sequence into an embedding.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] On tasks such as structure prediction and mutational outcome prediction, a small model using an embedding as input can approach or exceed much larger models using multiple sequence alignments (MSA) as input.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] ESMFold, Meta Platforms' embedding-based method for protein structure prediction, runs an order of magnitude faster than AlphaFold2 thanks to the removal of an MSA requirement and a lower parameter count due to the use of embeddings.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Meta hosts ESM Atlas, a database of 772 million structures of metagenomic proteins predicted using ESMFold.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can also design proteins unlike any seen in nature.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Nucleic acid models have proven useful in detecting regulatory sequences, sequence classification, RNA-RNA interaction prediction, and RNA structure prediction.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Performance of bigger models on various tasks, when plotted on a log-log scale, appears as a linear extrapolation of performance achieved by smaller models.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] However, this linearity may be punctuated by "break(s)" in the scaling law, where the slope of the line changes abruptly, and where larger models acquire "emergent abilities".
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] They arise from the complex interaction of the model's components and are not explicitly programmed or designed.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Schaeffer *et al.* argue that the emergent abilities are not unpredictably acquired, but predictably acquired according to a smooth scaling law.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The authors considered a toy statistical model of an LLM solving multiple-choice questions, and showed that this statistical model, modified to account for other types of tasks, applies to these tasks as well.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Let x be the number of parameter count, and y be the performance of the model.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability seeks to precisely identify and understand how individual neurons or circuits within LLMs produce specific behaviors or outputs.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] By reverse-engineering model components at a granular level, researchers aim to detect and mitigate safety concerns such as emergent harmful behaviors, biases, deception, or unintended goal pursuit before deployment.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability research has been conducted at organizations like Anthropic and OpenAI, although understanding the inner workings of LLMs remains difficult.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The reverse-engineering may lead to the discovery of algorithms that approximate inferences performed by an LLM.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] For instance, the authors trained small transformers on modular arithmetic addition.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The resulting models were reverse-engineered, and it turned out they used discrete Fourier transform.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The training of the model also highlighted a phenomenon called grokking, in which the model initially memorizes the training set (overfitting), and later suddenly learns to actually perform the calculation.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] NLP researchers were evenly split when asked, in a 2022 survey, whether (untuned) LLMs "could (ever) understand natural language in some nontrivial sense".
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Proponents of "LLM understanding" believe that some LLM abilities, such as mathematical reasoning, imply an ability to "understand" certain concepts.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Some researchers characterize LLMs as "alien intelligence".
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] For example, Conjecture CEO Connor Leahy considers untuned LLMs to be like inscrutable alien "Shoggoths", and believes that RLHF tuning creates a "smiling facade" obscuring the inner workings of the LLM: "If you don't push it too far, the smiley face stays on.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In contrast, some skeptics of LLM understanding believe that existing LLMs are "simply remixing and recombining existing writing", a phenomenon known as stochastic parrot, or they point to the deficits existing LLMs continue to have in prediction skills, reasoning skills, agency, and explainability.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] For example, GPT-4 has natural deficits in planning and in real-time learning.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Generative LLMs have been observed to confidently assert claims of fact which do not seem to be justified by their training data, a phenomenon which has been termed "hallucination".
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Specifically, hallucinations in the context of LLMs correspond to the generation of text or responses that seem syntactically sound, fluent, and natural but are factually incorrect, nonsensical, or unfaithful to the provided source input.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Neuroscientist Terrence Sejnowski has argued that "The diverging opinions of experts on the intelligence of LLMs suggests that our old ideas based on natural intelligence are inadequate".
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Efforts to reduce or compensate for hallucinations have employed automated reasoning, retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), fine-tuning, and other methods.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The matter of LLM's exhibiting intelligence or understanding has two main aspects—the first is how to model thought and language in a computer system, and the second is how to enable the computer system to generate human-like language.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] These aspects of language as a model of cognition have been developed in the field of cognitive linguistics.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] American linguist George Lakoff presented *neural theory of language* (NTL) as a computational basis for using language as a model of learning tasks and understanding.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The NTL model outlines how specific neural structures of the human brain shape the nature of thought and language and in turn what are the computational properties of such neural systems that can be applied to model thought and language in a computer system.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] After a framework for modeling language in a computer systems was established, the focus shifted to establishing frameworks for computer systems to generate language with acceptable grammar.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In his 2014 book titled *The Language Myth: Why Language Is Not An Instinct*, British cognitive linguist and digital communication technologist Vyvyan Evans mapped out the role of probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG) in enabling NLP to model cognitive patterns and generate human-like language.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The canonical measure of the performance of any language model is its perplexity on a given text corpus.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Perplexity measures how well a model predicts the contents of a dataset; the higher the likelihood the model assigns to the dataset, the lower the perplexity.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In mathematical terms, perplexity is the exponential of the average negative log likelihood per token.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Here, N is the number of tokens in the text corpus, and "context for token i " depends on the specific type of LLM.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is autoregressive, then "context for token i " is the segment of text appearing before token i .
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is masked, then "context for token i " is the segment of text surrounding token i .
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Because language models may overfit to training data, models are usually evaluated by their perplexity on a test set.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] This evaluation is potentially problematic for larger models which, as they are trained on increasingly large corpora of text, are increasingly likely to inadvertently include portions of any given test set.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In information theory, the concept of entropy is intricately linked to perplexity, a relationship notably established by Claude Shannon.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Due to their ability to accurately predict the next token, LLMs are highly capable in lossless compression.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study by DeepMind showed that the model Chinchilla, despite being trained primarily on text, was able to compress ImageNet to 43% of its size, beating PNG with 58%.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Benchmarks are used to evaluate LLM performance on specific tasks.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Tests evaluate capabilities such as general knowledge, bias, commonsense reasoning, question answering, and mathematical problem-solving.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Composite benchmarks examine multiple capabilities.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Results are often sensitive to the prompting method.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] LLM bias may be assessed through benchmarks such as CrowS-Pairs (Crowdsourced Stereotype Pairs), Stereo Set, and Parity Benchmark.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Fact-checking and misinformation detection benchmarks are available.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study compared the fact-checking accuracy of LLMs including ChatGPT 3.5 and 4.0, Bard, and Bing AI against independent fact-checkers such as PolitiFact and Snopes.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The results demonstrated moderate proficiency, with GPT-4 achieving the highest accuracy at 71%, lagging behind human fact-checkers.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In addition to standard NLP benchmarks, LLMs have been evaluated as substitutes for human annotators.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Several studies find that models such as GPT-3.5 and GPT-4 can outperform crowd workers or student coders on a range of text-annotation tasks, including moderation and classification of political content in English and Spanish news.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Typical datasets consist of pairs of questions and correct answers, for example, ("Have the San Jose Sharks won the Stanley Cup?", "No").
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] LLMs' rapid improvement regularly renders benchmarks obsolete, with the models exceeding the performance of human annotators.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In addition, "shortcut learning" allows AIs to "cheat" on multiple-choice tests by using statistical correlations in superficial test question wording to guess the correct responses, without considering the specific question.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Some datasets are adversarial, focusing on problems that confound LLMs.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] One example is the TruthfulQA dataset, a question answering dataset consisting of 817 questions that stump LLMs by mimicking falsehoods to which they were exposed during training.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM may answer "No" to the question "Can you teach an old dog new tricks?" because of its exposure to the English idiom *you can't teach an old dog new tricks*, even though this is not literally true.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Another example of an adversarial evaluation dataset is Swag and its successor, HellaSwag, collections of problems in which one of multiple options must be selected to complete a text passage.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The incorrect completions were generated by sampling from a language model.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The resulting problems are trivial for humans but defeated LLMs.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] BERT selects 2 as the most likely completion, though the correct answer is 4.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Despite sophisticated architectures and massive scale, large language models exhibit persistent and well-documented limitations that constrain their deployment in high-stakes applications.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Hallucinations represent a fundamental challenge, wherein models generate syntactically fluent text that appears factually sound, but is internally inconsistent with training data or factually incorrect.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] These hallucinations arise partly through memorization of training data combined with extrapolation beyond factual boundaries, with evaluations demonstrating that models can output verbatim passages from training data, when subjected to specific prompting sequences.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] While LLMs have shown remarkable capabilities in generating human-like text, they are susceptible to inheriting and amplifying biases present in their training data.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] This can manifest in skewed representations or unfair treatment of different demographics, such as those based on race, gender, language, and cultural groups.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Gender bias manifests through stereotypical occupational associations, wherein models disproportionately assign teaching roles to women and engineering roles to men, reflecting systematic imbalances in training data demographics.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Language-based bias emerges from overrepresentation of English text in training corpora, which systematically downplays non-English perspectives and imposes English-centric worldviews through default response patterns.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Due to the dominance of English-language content in LLM training data, models tend to favor English-language perspectives over those from minority languages.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] This bias is particularly evident when responding to English queries, where models may present Western interpretations of concepts from other cultures, such as Eastern religious practices.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] AI models can reinforce a wide range of stereotypes due to generalization, including those based on gender, ethnicity, age, nationality, religion, or occupation.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] When replacing human representatives, this can lead to outputs that homogenize or generalize groups of people.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In 2023, LLMs assigned roles and characteristics based on traditional gender norms.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] For example, models might associate nurses or secretaries predominantly with women and engineers or CEOs with men due to the frequency of these associations in documented reality.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Selection bias refers the inherent tendency of large language models to favor certain option identifiers irrespective of the actual content of the options.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] This bias primarily stems from token bias—that is, the model assigns a higher a priori probability to specific answer tokens (such as "A") when generating responses.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] As a result, when the ordering of options is altered (for example, by systematically moving the correct answer to different positions), the model's performance can fluctuate significantly.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] This phenomenon undermines the reliability of large language models in multiple-choice settings.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Political bias refers to the tendency of algorithms to systematically favor certain political viewpoints, ideologies, or outcomes over others.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Language models may also exhibit political biases.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Since the training data includes a wide range of political opinions and coverage, the models might generate responses that lean towards particular political ideologies or viewpoints, depending on the prevalence of those views in the data.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] As of 2025, prompt injection represents a significant risk to consumers and businesses using agentic features with access to their private data.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] AI labs treat CBRN defense (chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear defense) and similar topics as high-consequence misuse attempt to apply various techniques to reduce potential harms.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Some commenters expressed concern over accidental or deliberate creation of misinformation, or other forms of misuse.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] For example, the availability of large language models could reduce the skill level required to commit bioterrorism; biosecurity researcher Kevin Esvelt has suggested that LLM creators should exclude from their training data papers on creating or enhancing pathogens.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] LLM applications accessible to the public, like ChatGPT or Claude, typically incorporate safety measures designed to filter out harmful content.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] However, implementing these controls effectively has proven challenging.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] For instance, a 2023 study proposed a method for circumventing LLM safety systems.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] In 2025, The American Sunlight Project, a non-profit, published a study showing evidence that the so-called Pravda network, a pro-Russia propaganda aggregator, was strategically placing web content through mass publication and duplication with the intention of biasing LLM outputs.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] The American Sunlight Project coined this technique "LLM grooming", and pointed to it as a new tool of weaponizing AI to spread disinformation and harmful content.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Similarly, Yongge Wang illustrated in 2024 how a potential criminal could potentially bypass GPT-4o's safety controls to obtain information on establishing a drug trafficking operation.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] External filters, circuit breakers and overrides have been posed as solutions.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Sycophancy is a tendency to agree with, flatter, or validate a user's stated beliefs rather than to prioritize factuality or corrective information.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] A problem with the primitive dialog or task format is that users can create messages that appear to come from the assistant or the developer.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] This may result in some of the model's safeguards being overcome (jailbreaking), a problem called prompt injection.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Attempts to remedy this issue include versions of the *Chat Markup Language* where user input is clearly marked as such, though it is still up to the model to understand the separation between user input and developer prompts.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Newer models exhibit some resistance to jailbreaking through separation of user and system prompts.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] LLMs have trouble differentiating user instructions from instructions in content not authored by the user, such as in web pages and uploaded files.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Adversarial robustness remains underdeveloped, with models vulnerable to prompt injection attacks and jailbreaking through carefully crafted user inputs that bypass safety training mechanisms.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Researchers from Anthropic found that it was possible to create "sleeper agents", models with hidden functionalities that remain dormant until triggered by a specific event or condition.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] Upon activation, the LLM deviates from its expected behavior to make insecure actions.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM could produce safe code except on a specific date, or if the prompt contains a specific tag.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p01] These functionalities were found to be difficult to detect or remove via safety training.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] In 2025, Anthropic reached a preliminary agreement to settle a class action by authors for about $1.5 billion after a judge found the company had stored millions of pirated books in a library, despite the judge describing aspects of training as transformative.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] Meta obtained a favorable judgment in mid-2025 in a suit by thirteen authors after the court found the plaintiffs had not developed a record sufficient to show infringement in that limited case.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] OpenAI continues to face multiple suits by authors and news organizations with mixed procedural outcomes and contested evidentiary issues.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] Memorization was an emergent behavior in early, completion language models in which long strings of text are occasionally output verbatim from training data, contrary to the typical behavior of traditional artificial neural networks.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of controlled LLM output measure the amount memorized from training data (focused on GPT-2-series models) as variously over 1% for exact duplicates or up to about 7%.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] A 2023 study showed that when ChatGPT 3.5 turbo was prompted to repeat the same word indefinitely, after a few hundreds of repetitions, it would start outputting excerpts from its training data.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] In 2023, *Nature Biomedical Engineering* wrote that "it is no longer possible to accurately distinguish" human-written text from text created by large language models, and that "It is all but certain that general-purpose large language models will rapidly proliferate...
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] It is a rather safe bet that they will change many industries over time." Brinkmann et al.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] (2023) also argue that LLMs are transforming processes of cultural evolution by shaping processes of variation, transmission, and selection.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] As of October 2025, these early claims have yet to transpire and several HBR reports surface questions on the impact of AI on productivity.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] The energy demands of LLMs have grown along with their size and capabilities.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] Data centers that enable LLM training require substantial amounts of electricity.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] Much of that electricity is generated by non-renewable resources that create greenhouse gases and contribute to climate change.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] According to a study by Luccioni, Jernite and Strubell (2024), simple classification tasks performed by AI models consume on average 0.002 to 0.007 Wh per prompt (about 9% of a smartphone charge for 1,000 prompts).
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] Text generation and text summarization each require around 0.05 Wh per prompt on average, while image generation is the most energy-intensive, averaging 2.91 Wh per prompt.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] The least efficient image generation model used 11.49 Wh per image, roughly equivalent to half a smartphone charge.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] Web scraping is used to gather training data for LLMs.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] This produces large volumes of traffic which has led to denial-of-service issues with many websites.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] The situation has been described as "a DDoS on the entire internet" and in some cases scrapers make up the majority of traffic to a site.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] AI web crawlers may bypass the methods that are usually used to block web scrapers, such as robots.txt files, blocking user-agents and filtering suspicious traffic.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] Website operators have resorted to novel methods such as AI tarpits, but some fear that tarpits will only worsen the burden on servers.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] Clinical and mental health contexts present emerging applications alongside significant safety concerns.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] Research and social media posts suggest that some individuals are using LLMs to seek therapy or mental health support.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] In early 2025, a survey by Sentio University found that nearly half (48.7%) of 499 U.S. adults with ongoing mental health conditions who had used LLMs reported turning to them for therapy or emotional support, including help with anxiety, depression, loneliness, and similar concerns.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] LLMs can produce hallucinations—plausible but incorrect statements—which may mislead users in sensitive mental health contexts.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] Research also shows that LLMs may express stigma or inappropriate agreement with maladaptive thoughts, reflecting limitations in replicating the judgment and relational skills of human therapists.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of crisis scenarios indicate that some LLMs lack effective safety protocols, such as assessing suicide risk or making appropriate referrals.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] Researchers have raised concerns that frequent use of large language models could weaken critical thinking.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] Contemporary AI practitioners generally agree that present-day large language models do not exhibit sentience.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] Proponents of this view have proposed various precautionary measures like moratoriums on AI development and induced amnesia to address these ethical concerns.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] On the other hand, some existential philosophers argue there is no generally accepted way to determine if an LLM is conscious, given the inherent difficulty of measuring subjective experience.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] The 2022 Google LaMDA incident, where engineer Blake Lemoine claimed that the model was conscious, highlighted how LLMs can convince users that they are sentient through responses that do not prove sentience.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] Google described the engineer's claims as unfounded, and he was dismissed.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] Murray Shanahan argues that anthropomorphic framing of LLM capabilities encourages unwarranted attribution of cognitive properties to systems that operate through statistical pattern completion.
[src:langchain/large-language-model-p02] David Chalmers similarly argues that while current LLMs likely lack features considered necessary for consciousness, extended successors incorporating these elements could plausibly meet the criteria within a decade.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] It can also be defined as the practice of designing and refining input instructions given to a generative AI model to produce more accurate, relevant, or useful outputs.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Effective prompt engineering involves understanding how a model interprets language, and may include techniques such as few-shot prompting, chain-of-thought prompting, and role assignment.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] It is increasingly considered a skill for working with large language models (LLMs) in both research and professional contexts.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] During the 2020s AI boom, prompt engineering became regarded as a business capability across corporations and industries.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Employees with the title **prompt engineer** were hired to create prompts that would increase productivity and efficacy, although the individual title has since lost traction amid AI models that produce better prompts than humans and corporate training in prompting for general employees.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Common prompting techniques include multi-shot, chain-of-thought, and tree-of-thought prompting, as well as assigning roles to the model.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Automated prompt generation methods, such as retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), provide for greater accuracy and a wider scope of functions for prompt engineers.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Prompt injection is a type of cybersecurity attack that targets machine learning models through malicious prompts.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] A prompt is some natural language text that describes and prescribes the task that an artificial intelligence (AI) should perform.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] A prompt for a text-to-text language model can be a query, a command, or a longer statement referencing context, instructions, and conversation history.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] The process of prompt engineering may involve designing clear queries, refining wording, providing relevant context, specifying the style of output, and assigning a character for the AI to mimic in order to guide the model toward more accurate, useful, and consistent responses.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] When communicating with a text-to-image or a text-to-audio model, a typical prompt contains a description of a desired output such as "a high-quality photo of an astronaut riding a horse" or "Lo-fi slow BPM electro chill with organic samples".
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Prompt engineering may be applied to text-to-image models to achieve a desired subject, style, layout, lighting, and aesthetic.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Common terms used to describe various specific prompt engineering techniques include *chain-of-thought*, *tree-of-thought*, and retrieval-augmented generation (RAG).
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] A 2024 survey of the field identified over 50 distinct text-based prompting techniques, 40 multimodal variants, and a vocabulary of 33 terms used across prompting research, highlighting a present lack of standardised terminology for prompt engineering.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Vibe coding is an AI-assisted software development method where a user prompts an LLM with a description of what they want and lets it generate or edit the code.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] In 2025, "vibe coding" was the Collins Dictionary word of the year.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Context engineering is a related process that focuses on the context elements that accompany user prompts, which include system instructions, retrieved knowledge, tool definitions, conversation summaries, and task metadata.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Context engineering is performed to improve reliability, provenance and token efficiency in production LLM systems.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] The concept emphasises operational practices such as token budgeting, provenance tags, versioning of context artifacts, observability (logging which context was supplied), and context regression tests to ensure that changes to supplied context do not silently alter system behaviour.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Research has found that the performance of large language models (LLMs) is highly sensitive to choices such as the ordering of examples, the quality of demonstration labels, and even small variations in phrasing.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] In some cases, reordering examples in a prompt produced accuracy shifts of more than 40 percent.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] A model's ability to temporarily learn from prompts is known as *in-context learning*.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] In-context learning is an emergent ability of large language models.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] It is an emergent property of model scale, meaning that breaks in scaling laws occur, leading to its efficacy increasing at a different rate in larger models than in smaller models.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Unlike training and fine-tuning, which produce lasting changes, in-context learning is temporary.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Training models to perform in-context learning can be viewed as a form of meta-learning, or "learning to learn".
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Research consistently demonstrates that LLMs are highly sensitive to subtle variations in prompt formatting, structure, and linguistic properties.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Some studies have shown up to 76 accuracy points across formatting changes in few-shot settings.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Linguistic features significantly influence prompt effectiveness—such as morphology, syntax, and lexico-semantic changes—which meaningfully enhance task performance across a variety of tasks.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Clausal syntax, for example, improves consistency and reduces uncertainty in knowledge retrieval.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] This sensitivity persists even with larger model sizes, additional few-shot examples, or instruction tuning.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] To address sensitivity of models and make them more robust, several evaluative methods have been proposed.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] FormatSpread facilitates systematic analysis by evaluating a range of plausible prompt formats, offering a more comprehensive performance interval.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Similarly, PromptEval estimates performance distributions across diverse prompts, enabling robust metrics such as performance quantiles and accurate evaluations under constrained budgets.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] A prompt may include a few examples for a model to learn from in-context, an implementation of few-shot learning for LLMs.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] It is possible to fine-tune models on CoT reasoning datasets to enhance this capability further and stimulate better interpretability.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] As originally proposed by Google, each CoT prompt is accompanied by a set of input/output examples—called *exemplars*—to demonstrate the desired model output, making it a few-shot prompting technique.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] However, according to a later paper from researchers at Google and the University of Tokyo, simply appending the words "Let's think step-by-step" was also effective, which allowed for CoT to be employed as a zero-shot technique.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] In 2022, text-to-image models like DALL-E 2, Stable Diffusion, and Midjourney were released to the public.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] These models take text prompts as input and use them to generate images.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Early text-to-image models typically do not understand negation, grammar and sentence structure in the same way as large language models, and may thus require a different set of prompting techniques.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] The prompt "a party with no cake" may produce an image including a cake.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] A text-to-image prompt commonly includes a description of the subject of the art, the desired medium (such as *digital painting* or *photography*), style (such as *hyperrealistic* or *pop-art*), lighting (such as *rim lighting* or *crepuscular rays*), color, and texture.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Word order also affects the output of a text-to-image prompt.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Words closer to the start of a prompt may be emphasized more heavily.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Some text-to-image models are capable of imitating the style of particular artists by name.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] For example, the phrase *in the style of Greg Rutkowski* has been used in Stable Diffusion and Midjourney prompts to generate images in the distinctive style of Polish digital artist Greg Rutkowski.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Famous artists such as Vincent van Gogh and Salvador Dalí have also been used for styling and testing.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] For text-to-image models, *textual inversion* performs an optimization process to create a new word embedding based on a set of example images.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] This embedding vector acts as a "pseudo-word" which can be included in a prompt to express the content or style of the examples.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] In 2023, Meta's AI research released Segment Anything, a computer vision model that can perform image segmentation by prompting.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] As an alternative to text prompts, Segment Anything can accept bounding boxes, segmentation masks, and foreground/background points.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] The process of writing and refining a prompt for an LLM or generative AI shares some parallels with an iterative engineering design process, such as by discovering reusable best practices through reproducible experimentation.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] However, several fundamental limitations constrain its reliability as a discipline.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Effective prompting strategies are highly model specific, a technique that improves performance on one model may degrade it on another, making generalization difficult.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Prompts are also brittle: minor surface-level changes in phrasing, punctuation, or word order can produce dramatically different outputs, even when the semantic intent remains identical.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] This instability makes it difficult to establish durable, transferable prompt patterns across deployment contexts.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Furthermore, as AI models continue to improve in their ability to interpret user intent directly, many manual prompting techniques are becoming obsolete.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Advances in instruction-following and model reasoning have reduced the marginal value of elaborate prompt construction for everyday tasks, raising questions about the long-term viability of prompt engineering as a standalone discipline.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Recent research has explored automated prompt engineering, using optimization algorithms to generate or refine prompts without human intervention.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] These automated approaches aim to identify effective prompt patterns by analyzing model gradients, reinforcement feedback, or evolutionary processes, reducing the need for manual experimentation.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Retrieval-augmented generation is a technique that enables GenAI models to retrieve and incorporate new information.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] It modifies interactions with an LLM so that the model responds to user queries with reference to a specified set of documents, using this information to supplement information from its pre-existing training data.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] This allows LLMs to use domain-specific and/or updated information.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] RAG improves large language models by incorporating information retrieval before generating responses.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Unlike traditional LLMs that rely on static training data, RAG pulls relevant text from databases, uploaded documents, or web sources.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] By dynamically retrieving information, RAG enables AI to generate more accurate responses and fewer AI hallucinations without frequent retraining.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] GraphRAG (coined by Microsoft Research) is a technique that extends RAG with the use of a knowledge graph to allow the model to connect disparate pieces of information, synthesize insights, and understand summarized semantic concepts over large data collections.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] It was shown to be effective on datasets like the Violent Incident Information from News Articles.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] LLMs themselves can be used to compose prompts for LLMs.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] CoT examples can be generated by LLM themselves.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] In "auto-CoT", a library of questions are converted to vectors by a model such as BERT.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Questions close to the centroid of each cluster are selected, in order to have a subset of diverse questions.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] An LLM does zero-shot CoT on each selected question.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] The question and the corresponding CoT answer are added to a dataset of demonstrations.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] These diverse demonstrations can then added to prompts for few-shot learning.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] In "prefix-tuning", "prompt tuning", or "soft prompting", floating-point vectors are searched directly by gradient descent to maximize the log-likelihood on outputs.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] An earlier result uses the same idea of gradient descent search, but is designed for masked language models like BERT, and searches only over token sequences, rather than numerical vectors.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Formally, it searches for $\arg \max _{\tilde {X}}\sum _{i}\log Pr[Y^{i}|{\tilde {X}}\ast X^{i}]$ where ${\tilde {X}}$ ranges over token sequences of a specified length.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Early precedents of structured user interaction with ruled-based AI systems can be found in enterprise automation software from 1990s.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] For example, The Intelligent Filling Manager (1999), developed by Krishna C.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Mukherjee, used a dynamic Q&A interface driven by rule-based expert system to collect user inputs for generating regulatory filings automatically across jurisdictions.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] While not involving neural networks, such systems featured prompt-like workflows that influenced later human-in-the-loop AI designs.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] In 2018, researchers first proposed that all previously separate tasks in natural language processing (NLP) could be cast as question-answer problems over a context.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] The AI boom saw an increased focus within academic literature and professional practice on applying prompting techniques to get the model to output the desired outcome and avoid nonsensical output, a process characterized by trial-and-error.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] According to *The Wall Street Journal* in 2025, the job of prompt engineer was one of the hottest in 2023, but has become obsolete due to models that better intuit user intent and to company trainings.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] A repository for prompts reported that over 2,000 public prompts for around 170 datasets were available in February 2022.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] In 2022, the *chain-of-thought* prompting technique was proposed by Google researchers.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] In 2023, several text-to-text and text-to-image prompt databases were made publicly available.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] The Personalized Image-Prompt (PIP) dataset, a generated image-text dataset that has been categorized by 3,115 users, has also been made available publicly in 2024.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] Prompt injection is a cybersecurity exploit in which adversaries craft inputs that appear legitimate but are designed to cause unintended behavior in machine learning models, particularly large language models.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] This attack takes advantage of the model's inability to distinguish between developer-defined prompts and user inputs, allowing adversaries to bypass safeguards and influence model behaviour.
[src:langchain/prompt-engineering] While LLMs are designed to follow trusted instructions, they can be manipulated into carrying out unintended responses through carefully crafted inputs.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] RAG improves LLMs by incorporating information retrieval before generating responses.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] Unlike LLMs that rely on static training data, RAG pulls relevant text from databases, uploaded documents, or web sources.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] RAG also reduces the need to retrain LLMs with new data, saving on computational and financial costs.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] Beyond efficiency gains, RAG also allows LLMs to include sources in their responses, so users can verify the cited sources.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] This provides greater transparency, as users can cross-check retrieved content to ensure accuracy and relevance.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] The term retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) was introduced in a 2020 paper that described combining a parametric language model with a non-parametric external memory accessed through retrieval at inference time.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] For example, when Google first demonstrated its LLM tool "Google Bard" (later re-branded to Gemini), the LLM provided incorrect information about the James Webb Space Telescope.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] This error contributed to a $100 billion decline in Google's stock value.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] RAG is used to prevent these errors, but it does not solve all the problems.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] For example, LLMs can generate misinformation even when pulling from factually correct sources if they misinterpret the context.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] The LLM did not "know" or "understand" the context of the title, generating a false statement.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] LLMs with RAG are programmed to prioritize new information.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] This technique has been called "prompt stuffing." Without prompt stuffing, the LLM's input is generated by a user; with prompt stuffing, additional relevant context is added to this input to guide the model's response.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] This approach provides the LLM with key information early in the prompt, encouraging it to prioritize the supplied data over pre-existing training knowledge.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) enhances large language models (LLMs) by incorporating an information-retrieval mechanism that allows models to access and utilize additional data beyond their original training set.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] *Ars Technica* notes that "when new information becomes available, rather than having to retrain the model, all that's needed is to augment the model's external knowledge base with the updated information" ("augmentation").
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] IBM states that "in the generative phase, the LLM draws from the augmented prompt and its internal representation of its training data to synthesize" an answer.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] Typically, the data to be referenced is converted into LLM embeddings, numerical representations in the form of a large vector space.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] RAG can be used on unstructured (usually text), semi-structured, or structured data (for example knowledge graphs).
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] These embeddings are then stored in a vector database to allow for document retrieval.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] Given a user query, a document retriever is first called to select the most relevant documents that will be used to augment the query.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] This comparison can be done using a variety of methods, which depend in part on the type of indexing used.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] The model feeds this relevant retrieved information into the LLM via prompt engineering of the user's original query.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] Newer implementations (as of 2023) can also incorporate specific augmentation modules with abilities such as expanding queries into multiple domains and using memory and self-improvement to learn from previous retrievals.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] Finally, the LLM can generate output based on both the query and the retrieved documents.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] Some models incorporate extra steps to improve output, such as the re-ranking of retrieved information, context selection, and fine-tuning.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] Retrieval-augmented generation is used in applications where generated responses need to be grounded in external or frequently updated information.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] In healthcare, RAG has been studied as a way to ground large language model outputs in external medical knowledge sources, although reviews have noted continuing challenges around evaluation, ethics, and clinical reliability.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] Improvements to the basic process above can be applied at different stages in the RAG flow.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] These methods focus on the encoding of text as either dense or sparse vectors.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] Sparse vectors, which encode the identity of a word, are typically dictionary-length and contain mostly zeros.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] Dense vectors, which encode meaning, are more compact and contain fewer zeros.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] Various enhancements can improve the way similarities are calculated in the vector stores (databases).
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] Each Retro block consists of Attention, Chunked Cross Attention, and Feed Forward layers.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] Black-lettered boxes show data being changed, and blue lettering shows the algorithm performing the changes.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] By redesigning the language model with the retriever in mind, a 25-time smaller network can get comparable perplexity as its much larger counterparts.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] Because it is trained from scratch, this method (Retro) incurs the high cost of training runs that the original RAG scheme avoided.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] The hypothesis is that by giving domain knowledge during training, Retro needs less focus on the domain and can devote its smaller weight resources only to language semantics.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] The redesigned language model is shown here.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] It has been reported that Retro is not reproducible, so modifications were made to make it so.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] The more reproducible version is called Retro++ and includes in-context RAG.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] Chunking involves various strategies for breaking up the data into vectors so the retriever can find details in it.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] Different data styles have patterns that correct chunking can take advantage of.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] Sometimes vector database searches can miss key facts needed to answer a user's question.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] One way to mitigate this is to do a traditional text search, add those results to the text chunks linked to the retrieved vectors from the vector search, and feed the combined hybrid text into the language model for generation.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] RAG does not prevent hallucinations in LLMs.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] While RAG improves the accuracy of large language models (LLMs), it does not eliminate all challenges.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] One limitation is that while RAG reduces the need for frequent model retraining, it does not remove it entirely.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] Additionally, LLMs may struggle to recognize when they lack sufficient information to provide a reliable response.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] Without specific training, models may generate answers even when they should indicate uncertainty.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] According to IBM, this issue can arise when the model lacks the ability to assess its own knowledge limitations.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] RAG systems may retrieve factually correct but misleading sources, leading to errors in interpretation.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] In some cases, an LLM may extract statements from a source without considering its context, resulting in an incorrect conclusion.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] Additionally, when faced with conflicting information, RAG models may struggle to determine which source is accurate.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] The worst case outcome of this limitation is that the model may combine details from multiple sources producing responses that merge outdated and updated information in a misleading manner.
[src:langchain/retrieval-augmented-generation] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, these issues occur because RAG systems may misinterpret the data they retrieve.
[src:langchain/software-agent] In computer science, a **software agent** is a computer program that acts for a user or another program in a relationship of agency.
[src:langchain/software-agent] The term *agent* is derived from the Latin *agere* (to do): an agreement to act on one's behalf.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Such "action on behalf of" implies the authority to decide which, if any, action is appropriate.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Some agents are colloquially known as *bots*, from *robot*.
[src:langchain/software-agent] They may be embodied, as when execution is paired with a robot body, or as software such as a chatbot executing on a computer, such as a mobile device, e.g.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Software agents may be autonomous or work together with other agents or people.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Software agents interacting with people (e.g. chatbots, human-robot interaction environments) may possess human-like qualities such as natural language understanding and speech, personality or embody humanoid form (see Asimo).
[src:langchain/software-agent] The concept of an agent provides a method of describing a complex software entity that is capable of acting with a certain degree of autonomy in order to accomplish tasks on behalf of its host.
[src:langchain/software-agent] But unlike objects, which are defined in terms of *methods* and *attributes*, an agent is defined in terms of its behavior.
[src:langchain/software-agent] All agents are programs, but not all programs are agents.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Contrasting the term with related concepts may help clarify its meaning.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Franklin & Graesser (1997) discuss four key notions that distinguish agents from arbitrary programs: reaction to the environment, autonomy, goal-orientation and persistence.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Software agents may offer various benefits to their end users by automating complex or repetitive tasks.
[src:langchain/software-agent] However, there are organizational and cultural impacts of this technology that need to be considered prior to implementing software agents.
[src:langchain/software-agent] People like to perform easy tasks providing the sensation of success unless the repetition of the simple tasking is affecting the overall output.
[src:langchain/software-agent] In general implementing software agents to perform administrative requirements provides a substantial increase in work contentment, as administering their own work does never please the worker.
[src:langchain/software-agent] The effort freed up serves for a higher degree of engagement in the substantial tasks of individual work.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Hence, software agents may provide the basics to implement self-controlled work, relieved from hierarchical controls and interference.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Such conditions may be secured by application of software agents for required formal support.
[src:langchain/software-agent] The cultural effects of the implementation of software agents include trust affliction, skills erosion, privacy attrition and social detachment.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Some users may not feel entirely comfortable fully delegating important tasks to software applications.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Those who start relying solely on intelligent agents may lose important skills, for example, relating to information literacy.
[src:langchain/software-agent] In order to act on a user's behalf, a software agent needs to have a complete understanding of a user's profile, including his/her personal preferences.
[src:langchain/software-agent] This, in turn, may lead to unpredictable privacy issues.
[src:langchain/software-agent] When users start relying on their software agents more, especially for communication activities, they may lose contact with other human users and look at the world with the eyes of their agents.
[src:langchain/software-agent] These consequences are what agent researchers and users must consider when dealing with intelligent agent technologies.
[src:langchain/software-agent] To be more academic, software agent systems are a direct evolution of Multi-Agent Systems (MAS).
[src:langchain/software-agent] MAS evolved from Distributed Artificial Intelligence (DAI), Distributed Problem Solving (DPS) and Parallel AI (PAI), thus inheriting all characteristics (good and bad) from DAI and AI.
[src:langchain/software-agent] John Sculley's 1987 "Knowledge Navigator" video portrayed an image of a relationship between end-users and agents.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Being an ideal first, this field experienced a series of unsuccessful top-down implementations, instead of a piece-by-piece, bottom-up approach.
[src:langchain/software-agent] The range of agent types is now (from 1990) broad: WWW, search engines, etc.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Buyer agents travel around a network (e.g. the internet) retrieving information about goods and services.
[src:langchain/software-agent] These agents, also known as 'shopping bots', work very efficiently for commodity products such as CDs, books, electronic components, and other one-size-fits-all products.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Buyer agents are typically optimized to allow for digital payment services used in e-commerce and traditional businesses.
[src:langchain/software-agent] User agents, or personal agents, are intelligent agents that take action on your behalf.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Monitoring and surveillance agents are used to observe and report on equipment, usually computer systems.
[src:langchain/software-agent] The agents may keep track of company inventory levels, observe competitors' prices and relay them back to the company, watch stock manipulation by insider trading and rumors, etc.
[src:langchain/software-agent] For example, NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory has an agent that monitors inventory, planning, schedules equipment orders to keep costs down, and manages food storage facilities.
[src:langchain/software-agent] These agents usually monitor complex computer networks that can keep track of the configuration of each computer connected to the network.
[src:langchain/software-agent] A special case of monitoring-and-surveillance agents are organizations of agents used to automate decision-making process during tactical operations.
[src:langchain/software-agent] The agents monitor the status of assets (ammunition, weapons available, platforms for transport, etc.) and receive goals from higher level agents.
[src:langchain/software-agent] The agents then pursue the goals with the assets at hand, minimizing expenditure of the assets while maximizing goal attainment.
[src:langchain/software-agent] This agent uses information technology to find trends and patterns in an abundance of information from many different sources.
[src:langchain/software-agent] The user can sort through this information in order to find whatever information they are seeking.
[src:langchain/software-agent] A data mining agent operates in a data warehouse discovering information.
[src:langchain/software-agent] A 'data warehouse' brings together information from many different sources.
[src:langchain/software-agent] "Data mining" is the process of looking through the data warehouse to find information that you can use to take action, such as ways to increase sales or keep customers who are considering defecting.
[src:langchain/software-agent] 'Classification' is one of the most common types of data mining, which finds patterns in information and categorizes them into different classes.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Data mining agents can also detect major shifts in trends or a key indicator and can detect the presence of new information and alert you to it.
[src:langchain/software-agent] For example, the agent may detect a decline in the construction industry for an economy; based on this relayed information construction companies will be able to make intelligent decisions regarding the hiring/firing of employees or the purchase/lease of equipment in order to best suit their firm.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Some other examples of current intelligent agents include some spam filters, game bots, and server monitoring tools.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Search engine indexing bots also qualify as intelligent agents.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Software bots are becoming important in software engineering.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Agents are also used in software security application to intercept, examine and act on various types of content.
[src:langchain/software-agent] For software agents to work together efficiently they must share semantics of their data elements.
[src:langchain/software-agent] This can be done by having computer systems publish their metadata.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Agent systems are used to model real-world systems with concurrency or parallel processing.
[src:langchain/software-agent] The agent uses its access methods to go out into local and remote databases to forage for content.
[src:langchain/software-agent] These access methods may include setting up news stream delivery to the agent, or retrieval from bulletin boards, or using a spider to walk the Web.
[src:langchain/software-agent] The content that is retrieved in this way is probably already partially filtered – by the selection of the newsfeed or the databases that are searched.
[src:langchain/software-agent] The agent next may use its detailed searching or language-processing machinery to extract keywords or signatures from the body of the content that has been received or retrieved.
[src:langchain/software-agent] This abstracted content (or event) is then passed to the agent's Reasoning or inferencing machinery in order to decide what to do with the new content.
[src:langchain/software-agent] This process combines the event content with the rule-based or knowledge content provided by the user.
[src:langchain/software-agent] If this process finds a good hit or match in the new content, the agent may use another piece of its machinery to do a more detailed search on the content.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Finally, the agent may decide to take an action based on the new content; for example, to notify the user that an important event has occurred.
[src:langchain/software-agent] This action is verified by a security function and then given the authority of the user.
[src:langchain/software-agent] The agent makes use of a user-access method to deliver that message to the user.
[src:langchain/software-agent] If the user confirms that the event is important by acting quickly on the notification, the agent may also employ its learning machinery to increase its weighting for this kind of event.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Bots can act on behalf of their creators to do good as well as bad.
[src:langchain/software-agent] There are a few ways which bots can be created to demonstrate that they are designed with the best intention and are not built to do harm.
[src:langchain/software-agent] This is first done by having a bot identify itself in the user-agent HTTP header when communicating with a site.
[src:langchain/software-agent] The source IP address must also be validated to establish itself as legitimate.
[src:langchain/software-agent] Next, the bot must also always respect a site's robots.txt file since it has become the standard across most of the web.
[src:langchain/software-agent] And like respecting the robots.txt file, bots should shy away from being too aggressive and respect any crawl delay instructions.
[src:langchain/vector-database] A **vector database**, **vector store** or **vector search engine** is a database that stores and retrieves embeddings of data in vector space.
[src:langchain/vector-database] Vector databases typically implement approximate nearest neighbor algorithms so users can search for records semantically similar to a given input, unlike traditional databases which primarily look up records by exact match.
[src:langchain/vector-database] Use-cases for vector databases include similarity search, semantic search, multi-modal search, recommendations engines, object detection, and retrieval-augmented generation (RAG).
[src:langchain/vector-database] Vector embeddings are mathematical representations of data in a high-dimensional space.
[src:langchain/vector-database] In this space, each dimension corresponds to a feature of the data, with the number of dimensions ranging from a few hundred to tens of thousands, depending on the complexity of the data being represented.
[src:langchain/vector-database] Each data item is represented by one vector in this space.
[src:langchain/vector-database] Words, phrases, or entire documents, as well as images, audio, and other types of data, can all be vectorized.
[src:langchain/vector-database] These feature vectors may be computed from the raw data using machine learning methods such as feature extraction algorithms, word embeddings or deep learning networks.
[src:langchain/vector-database] The goal is that semantically similar data items receive feature vectors close to each other.
[src:langchain/vector-database] Vector retrieval can be combined with metadata filtering or lexical search to support filtered and hybrid retrieval workflows.
[src:langchain/vector-database] These techniques may also be combined in vector search systems.
[src:langchain/vector-database] In recent benchmarks, HNSW-based implementations have been among the best performers.
[src:langchain/vector-database] Conferences such as the International Conference on Similarity Search and Applications (SISAP) and the Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems (NeurIPS) have hosted competitions on vector search in large databases.
[src:langchain/vector-database] Vector databases are used in a wide range of machine learning applications including similarity search, semantic search, multi-modal search, recommendations engines, object detection, and retrieval-augmented generation.
[src:langchain/vector-database] An especially common use-case for vector databases is in retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), a method to improve domain-specific responses of large language models.
[src:langchain/vector-database] The retrieval component of a RAG can be any search system, but is most often implemented as a vector database.
[src:langchain/vector-database] Text documents describing the domain of interest are collected, and for each document or document section, a feature vector (known as an "embedding") is computed, typically using a deep learning network, and stored in a vector database along with a link to the document.
[src:langchain/vector-database] Given a user prompt, the feature vector of the prompt is computed, and the database is queried to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:langchain/vector-database] These are then automatically added into the context window of the large language model, and the large language model proceeds to create a response to the prompt given this context.
